'''Alfred Eliasson''' (1920 - 1988) was an [[Icelanders|Icelandic]] businessman who founded and served as president of [[Icelandic Airlines|Loftleidir]].<ref>{{cite web |title=A Plane Crash, A Glacier, And An Entrepreneur: How Icelandair Opened Up Air Travel For Everyone |url=https://www.fastcompany.com/40414742/a-plane-crash-a-glacier-an-entrepreneur-how-icelandair-opened-up-air-travel-for-everyone |website=Fast Company |accessdate=28 June 2018 |date=26 May 2017}}</ref>

Loftleiðir Icelandic Airlines was formed in 1944 with a single engine, three passenger plane of [[Stinson Reliant]] make, Loftleiðir grew to become one of the major carriers of the North Atlantic in the 1960s and early 1970s pioneering low cost air travel over the Atlantic.<ref>{{cite web |title=Icelandic Airlines History: The Country's Latest and Greatest |url=https://tedium.co/2017/05/29/iceland-airlines-history/ |website=Tedium: The Dull Side of the Internet. |accessdate=28 June 2018 |date=30 May 2017}}</ref>

He has had his story made into a documentary film called ''Alfred Eliasson & Loftleiðir Icelandic'' made in 2009 in Iceland, which tells the story of the airline and Alfred, narrated in Icelandic by [[Arnar Jónsson (actor)|Arnar Jónsson]].{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}

