{{Big Five Hawaii}} The '''Big Five''' ({{lang-haw|Nā Hui Nui {{okina}}Elima}}) was the name given to a group of what started as [[sugarcane]] processing [[corporations]] that wielded considerable political power in the [[Territory of Hawaii]] during the early 20th century and leaned heavily towards the [[Republican Party of Hawaii|Hawaii Republican Party]]. The Big Five were [[Castle & Cooke]], [[Alexander & Baldwin]], [[C. Brewer & Co.]], American Factors (now [[Amfac (Hawaii)|Amfac]]), and [[Theo H. Davies & Co.]]<ref name="adv">{{cite news |title=Isle institutions’ economic impact endures |author=Lyn Danninger |url=http://starbulletin.com/2002/09/29/special/story3.html |publisher=[[Honolulu Star-Bulletin]] |date=September 29, 2002 |accessdate= 2010-05-01 }}</ref> The extent of the power that the Big Five had was considered by some as equivalent to an [[oligarchy]]. [[Attorney General of Hawaii]] [[Edmund Pearson Dole]], referring to the Big Five, said in 1903, "There is a government in this Territory which is centralized to an extent unknown in the United States, and probably almost as centralized as it was in France under [[Louis XIV]]."<ref name="benham1998">{{cite book |title=Culture and educational policy in Hawaiʻi: the silencing of native voices |year=1998 |publisher=Psychology Press |isbn=0-8058-2704-8 |author=Maenette Kapeʻahiokalani Padeken Ah Nee-Benham |author2=Ronald H. Heck |page=137}}</ref>
== History == Sugar plantations in Hawaii had a slow start, although the plant had been cultivated for hundreds of years.{{Citation needed|date=February 2010}} When Hawaii was [[Overthrow of the Kingdom of Hawaii#Annexation|annexed by the United States]], change came rapidly as sugarcane [[Sugar plantations in Hawaii|plantation]]s gained a new infusion of investment. By eliminating tariffs imposed on sugarcane producers by the United States, planters had more money to spend on equipment, land and labor. Increased capital resulted in increased production. Five kingdom-era corporations benefited from annexation, becoming multimillion-dollar conglomerations that controlled 90% of the sugar business.<ref>{{cite journal |hdl= 10524/462 |title= German Sugar's Sticky Fingers |journal= Hawaiian Journal of History |publisher=Hawaiian Historical Society |volume= 16 |author= Frederick Bernays Wiener |year= 1982 |pages= 15–47}}</ref> The companies colluded to keep the prices on their goods and services high. Their profits skyrocketed even more. Soon, the executives of the Big Five sat on each other's boards of directors. With economic power came political power, and the families usually favored the [[Republican Party of Hawaii]].<ref>{{cite news |title= Where Aristocrats Do the Hula and Vote Republican; Land and Commerce Screens From Japan New England Heritage Attended Punahou Cousins Society Plumeria and Orchids |date= November 27, 1966 |author1= Charlotte Curtis |author2= Carl T. Gossett Jr. |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |url= http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F10710FE3D59157A8EDDAE0A94D9415B868AF1D3 }}</ref>
During the [[Hawaii Democratic Revolution of 1954|Democratic Revolution of 1954]], the [[Trade union|unions]] inflicted a decisive blow against the giants and the sugar industry declined after [[Hawaii]] became a state in 1959; so did each of the Big Five companies.{{Citation needed|date=February 2010}} The greatest post-statehood challenge came as the [[U.S. Department of Justice]] challenged the ownership of [[Matson Navigation Company]] by four of the five companies (all except Theo H. Davies). The lawsuit was settled when the four companies agreed not to share officers, executives, and directors. Alexander and Baldwin eventually bought out the other three stakes in Matson in 1964.<ref name="adv"/>
In the 1970s, as sugar plantations closed, many of the Big Five companies themselves were bought out. Where the companies are now:{{Citation needed|date=February 2010}}
* [[Theo H. Davies]] was bought in 1973 by Scottish-controlled Hong Kong firm [[Jardine Matheson Holdings|Jardine Matheson]]. Until December 2004 it owned the [[Pizza Hut]] and [[Taco Bell]] franchises in Hawaii. * [[C. Brewer]] was bought in 1978 by Philadelphia-based [[IU International]], and was later bought out by its management in 1986. In 2001 the company's shareholders voted to liquidate the company over several years. * [[Castle & Cooke]] merged with [[Flexi-Van Corporation]], owned by [[David H. Murdock]], in 1985. Murdock became its chairman after the merger, then took full control in 2000. It still owns large portions of Central [[Oahu|O{{okina}}ahu]] and the Iwilei area of [[Honolulu]] around the former [[Dole Food Company]] pineapple cannery. Until recently, Castle & Cooke owned nearly all of the island of [[Lanai|Lāna{{okina}}i]]; in June 2012, Oracle CEO [[Larry Ellison]] bought their share for approximately half a billion dollars.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2012/06/20/BAT21P5CLG.DTL&tsp=1 |date=20 June 2012 |last=Lagos |first=Maria |title=Oracle's Ellison is buying a Hawaiian island |newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]}}</ref> * [[Amfac]] was bought out in 1988 by Chicago-based [[JMB Realty]]. In 2002 Amfac declared [[Chapter 11, Title 11, United States Code|Chapter 11 bankruptcy]] and emerged as Kaanapali Land, LLC. It owns 5,000 acres (20&nbsp;km²) in West Maui. Its department store, [[Liberty House (US)|Liberty House]], was sold to [[Federated Department Stores]] and is now part of the [[Macy's]] chain. * [[Alexander & Baldwin]] diversified and remains in business. Today it owns about 91,000 acres (370&nbsp;km²) of land and is the fifth-largest landowner in the state.{{Citation needed|date=February 2010}}
==In fiction== The domination of Hawaii by the Big Five forms much of the background for the book ''[[The Revolt of Mamie Stover]]'', describing the life of a prostitute in Hawaii in the 1940s.{{Citation needed|date=February 2010}}
James Michener's fictionalized account of Hawaiian history, ''[[Hawaii (novel)|Hawaii]]'' included references to the Big Five, which he called "the Fort".{{Citation needed|date=February 2010}}
The Big Five are mentioned briefly in [[Harry Turtledove]]'s ''[[Days of Infamy series]]'', an [[alternate history]] where [[Empire of Japan|Japanese]] forces completely occupy Hawaii during World War II.
The Big Five are mentioned in Kaye Starbird's THE LION IN THE LEI SHOP (p.&nbsp;43).
